# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: semiconductor-fabrication
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Typically, CMP uses cerium dioxide as the abrasive.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The process uses an abrasive and corrosive chemical slurry (commonly a colloid) in conjunction with a polishing pad and retaining ring, typically of a greater diameter than the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The pad and wafer are pressed together by a dynamic polishing head and held in place by a plastic retaining ring.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The dynamic polishing head is rotated with different axes of rotation (i.e., not concentric).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] This removes material and tends to even out any irregular topography, making the wafer flat or planar.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] This may be necessary to set up the wafer for the formation of additional circuit elements.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] For example, CMP can bring the entire surface within the depth of field of a photolithography system, or selectively remove material based on its position.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Typical depth-of-field requirements are down to Angstrom levels for the latest 22 nm technology.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Typical CMP tools, such as the ones seen on the right, consist of rotating an extremely flat plate which is covered by a pad.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The wafer that is being polished is mounted upside-down in a carrier/spindle on a backing film.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The retaining ring (Figure 1) keeps the wafer in the correct horizontal position.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] During the process of loading and unloading the wafer onto the tool, the wafer is held by vacuum by the carrier to prevent unwanted particles from building up on the wafer surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] A slurry introduction mechanism deposits the slurry on the pad, represented by the slurry supply in Figure 1.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Both the plate and the carrier are then rotated and the carrier is kept oscillating; this can be better seen in the top view of Figure 2.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] A downward pressure/down force is applied to the carrier, pushing it against the pad; typically the down force is an average force, but local pressure is needed for the removal mechanisms.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Down force depends on the contact area which, in turn, is dependent on the structures of both the wafer and the pad.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Typically the pads have a roughness of 50 μm; contact is made by asperities (which typically are the high points on the wafer) and, as a result, the contact area is only a fraction of the wafer area.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In CMP, the mechanical properties of the wafer itself must be considered too.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] If the wafer has a slightly bowed structure, the pressure will be greater on the edges than it would on the center, which causes non-uniform polishing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In order to compensate for the wafer bow, pressure can be applied to the wafer's backside which, in turn, will equalize the centre-edge differences.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The pads used in the CMP tool should be rigid in order to uniformly polish the wafer surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] However, these rigid pads must be kept in alignment with the wafer at all times.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Therefore, real pads are often just stacks of soft and hard materials that conform to wafer topography to some extent.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Generally, these pads are made from porous polymeric materials with a pore size between 30 and 50 μm, and because they are consumed in the process, they must be regularly reconditioned.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In most cases the pads are very much proprietary, and are usually referred to by their trademark names rather than their chemical or other properties.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Before about 1990 CMP was viewed as too "dirty" to be included in high-precision fabrication processes, since abrasion tends to create particles and the abrasives themselves are not without impurities.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Since that time, the integrated circuit industry has moved from aluminum to copper conductors.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] This required the development of an *additive patterning* process, which relies on the unique abilities of CMP to remove material in a planar and uniform fashion and to stop repeatably at the interface between copper and oxide insulating layers (see Copper interconnects for details).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Adoption of this process has made CMP processing much more widespread.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In addition to aluminum and copper, CMP processes have been developed for polishing tungsten, and silicon dioxide.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] There are currently several limitations of CMP that appear during the polishing process requiring optimization of a new technology.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In particular, an improvement in wafer metrology is required .
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In addition, it was discovered that the CMP process has several potential defects including stress cracking, delaminating at weak interfaces, and corrosive attacks from slurry chemicals.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] The oxide polishing process, which is the oldest and most used in today's industry, has one problem: a lack of end points requires blind polishing, making it hard to determine when the desired amount of material has been removed or the desired degree of planarization has been obtained.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] If the oxide layer has not been sufficiently thinned and/or the desired degree of planarity has not been achieved during this process, then (theoretically) the wafer can be repolished, but in a practical sense this is unattractive in production and is to be avoided if at all possible.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] If the oxide thickness is too thin or too non-uniform, then the wafer must be reworked, an even less attractive process and one that is likely to fail.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Obviously, this method is time-consuming and costly since technicians have to be more attentive while performing this process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Shallow trench isolation (STI), a process used to fabricate semiconductor devices, is a technique used to enhance the isolation between devices and active areas.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Moreover, STI has a higher degree of planarity making it essential in photolithographic applications, depth of focus budget by decreasing minimum line width.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] To planarize shallow trenches, a common method should be used such as the combination of resist etching-back (REB) and chemical mechanical polishing (CMP).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] This process comes in a sequence pattern as follows.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] First, the isolation trench pattern is transferred to the silicon wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Oxide is deposited on the wafer in the shape of trenches.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] A photo mask, composed of silicon nitride, is patterned on the top of this sacrificial oxide.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] A second layer is added to the wafer to create a planar surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] After that, the silicon is thermally oxidized, so the oxide grows in regions where there is no Si3N4 and the growth is between 0.5 and 1.0 μm thick.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Since the oxidizing species such as water or oxygen are unable to diffuse through the mask, the nitride prevents the oxidation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Next, the etching process is used to etch the wafer and leave a small amount of oxide in the active areas.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] In the end, CMP is used to polish the SiO2 overburden with an oxide on the active area.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Key manufacturers and suppliers in the field of CMP include equipment vendors such as Applied Materials and Ebara Corporation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/chemical-mechanical-polishing] Suppliers of consumable polishing pads and slurries include Entegris, Qnity Electronics, Merck, Fujifilm, Hitachi, 3M, and Resonac.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] For many etch steps, part of the wafer is protected from the etchant by a "masking" material which resists etching.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] In some cases, the masking material is a photoresist which has been patterned using photolithography.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Other situations require a more durable mask, such as silicon nitride.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The two fundamental types of etchants are liquid-phase ("wet") and plasma-phase ("dry").
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Each of these exists in several varieties.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The first etching processes used liquid-phase ("wet") etchants.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] This process is now largely outdated but was used up until the late 1980s when it was superseded by dry plasma etching.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The wafer can be immersed in a bath of etchant, which must be agitated to achieve good process control.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] For instance, buffered hydrofluoric acid (BHF) is used commonly to etch silicon dioxide over a silicon substrate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Different specialized etchants can be used to characterize the surface etched.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Wet etchants are usually isotropic, which leads to a large bias when etching thick films.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] They also require the disposal of large amounts of toxic waste.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] For these reasons, they are seldom used in state-of-the-art processes.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] However, the photographic developer used for photoresist resembles wet etching.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] As an alternative to immersion, single wafer machines use the Bernoulli principle to employ a gas (usually, pure nitrogen) to cushion and protect one side of the wafer while etchant is applied to the other side.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] It can be done to either the front side or back side.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The etch chemistry is dispensed on the top side when in the machine and the bottom side is not affected.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] This etching method is particularly effective just before "backend" processing (BEOL), where wafers are normally very much thinner after wafer backgrinding, and very sensitive to thermal or mechanical stress.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Etching a thin layer of even a few micrometres will remove microcracks produced during backgrinding resulting in the wafer having dramatically increased strength and flexibility without breaking.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Some wet etchants etch crystalline materials at very different rates depending upon which crystal face is exposed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] In single-crystal materials (e.g. silicon wafers), this effect can allow very high anisotropy, as shown in the figure.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The term "crystallographic etching" is synonymous with "anisotropic etching along crystal planes".
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] However, for some non-crystal materials like glass, there are unconventional ways to etch in an anisotropic manner.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The authors employ multistream laminar flow that contains etching non-etching solutions to fabricate a glass groove.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The etching solution at the center is flanked by non-etching solutions and the area contacting etching solutions is limited by the surrounding non-etching solutions.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The etching direction is thereby mainly vertical to the glass surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The scanning electron microscopy (SEM) images demonstrate the breaking of the conventional theoretical limit of aspect ratio (width/height=0.5) and contribute a two-fold improvement (width/height=1).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Several anisotropic wet etchants are available for silicon, all of them hot aqueous caustics.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] For instance, potassium hydroxide (KOH) displays an etch rate selectivity 400 times higher in <100> crystal directions than in <111> directions.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] EDP (an aqueous solution of ethylene diamine and pyrocatechol), displays a <100>/<111> selectivity of 17X, does not etch silicon dioxide as KOH does, and also displays high selectivity between lightly doped and heavily boron-doped (p-type) silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Use of these etchants on wafers that already contain CMOS integrated circuits requires protecting the circuitry.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] KOH may introduce mobile potassium ions into silicon dioxide, and EDP is highly corrosive and carcinogenic, so care is required in their use.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Tetramethylammonium hydroxide (TMAH) presents a safer alternative than EDP, with a 37X selectivity between {100} and {111} planes in silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Etching a (100) silicon surface through a rectangular hole in a masking material, like a hole in a layer of silicon nitride, creates a pit with flat sloping {111}-oriented sidewalls and a flat (100)-oriented bottom.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] If the etching is continued "to completion", i.e. until the flat bottom disappears, the pit becomes a trench with a V-shaped cross-section.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] If the original rectangle was a perfect square, the pit when etched to completion displays a pyramidal shape.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] where *R*xxx is the etch rate in the <xxx> direction, *T* is the etch time, *D* is the etch depth and *S* is the anisotropy of the material and etchant.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Different etchants have different anisotropies.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Modern very large scale integration (VLSI) processes avoid wet etching, and use *plasma etching* instead.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Plasma etchers can operate in several modes by adjusting the parameters of the plasma.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Ordinary plasma etching operates between 0.1 and 5 Torr.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] (This unit of pressure, commonly used in vacuum engineering, equals approximately 133.3 pascals.) The plasma produces energetic free radicals, neutrally charged, that react at the surface of the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Since neutral particles attack the wafer from all angles, this process is isotropic.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Plasma etching can be isotropic, i.e., exhibiting a lateral undercut rate on a patterned surface approximately the same as its downward etch rate, or can be anisotropic, i.e., exhibiting a smaller lateral undercut rate than its downward etch rate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Such anisotropy is maximized in deep reactive ion etching (DRIE).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The use of the term anisotropy for plasma etching should not be conflated with the use of the same term when referring to orientation-dependent etching.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The source gas for the plasma usually contains small molecules rich in chlorine or fluorine.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] For instance, carbon tetrachloride (CCl4) etches silicon and aluminium, and trifluoromethane etches silicon dioxide and silicon nitride.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] A plasma containing oxygen is used to oxidize ("ash") photoresist and facilitate its removal.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] If the etch is intended to make a cavity in a material, the depth of the cavity may be controlled approximately using the etching time and the known etch rate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] More often, though, etching must entirely remove the top layer of a multilayer structure, without damaging the underlying or masking layers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The etching system's ability to do this depends on the ratio of etch rates in the two materials (*selectivity*).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Some etches undercut the masking layer and form cavities with sloping sidewalls.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] The distance of undercutting is called *bias*.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Etchants with large bias are called *isotropic*, because they erode the substrate equally in all directions.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/etching-microfabrication] Modern processes greatly prefer *anisotropic* etches, because they produce sharp, well-controlled features.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Thus ion implantation is a special case of particle radiation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Each ion is typically a single atom or molecule, and thus the actual amount of material implanted in the target is the integral over time of the ion current.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The currents supplied by implants are typically small (micro-amperes), and thus the dose which can be implanted in a reasonable amount of time is small.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Therefore, ion implantation finds application in cases where the amount of chemical change required is small.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Typical ion energies are in the range of 10 to 500 keV (1,600 to 80,000 aJ).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Energies in the range 1 to 10 keV (160 to 1,600 aJ) can be used, but result in a penetration of only a few nanometers or less.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Energies lower than this result in very little damage to the target, and fall under the designation ion beam deposition.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Higher energies can also be used: accelerators capable of 5 MeV (800,000 aJ) are common.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] However, there is often great structural damage to the target, and because the depth distribution is broad (Bragg peak), the net composition change at any point in the target will be small.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The energy of the ions, as well as the ion species and the composition of the target determine the depth of penetration of the ions in the solid: A monoenergetic ion beam will generally have a broad depth distribution.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The average penetration depth is called the range of the ions.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Under typical circumstances ion ranges will be between 10 nanometers and 1 micrometer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Thus, ion implantation is especially useful in cases where the chemical or structural change is desired to be near the surface of the target.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ions gradually lose their energy as they travel through the solid, both from occasional collisions with target atoms (which cause abrupt energy transfers) and from a mild drag from overlap of electron orbitals, which is a continuous process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The loss of ion energy in the target is called stopping and can be simulated with the binary collision approximation method.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] All varieties of ion implantation beamline designs contain general groups of functional components (see image).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The first major segment of an ion beamline includes an ion source used to generate the ion species.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The source is closely coupled to biased electrodes for extraction of the ions into the beamline and most often to some means of selecting a particular ion species for transport into the main accelerator section.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The ion source is often made of materials with a high melting point such as tungsten, tungsten doped with lanthanum oxide (lanthanated tungsten), molybdenum and tantalum.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Lanthanum oxide helps extend the life of the ion source.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Arsine gas or phosphine gas can be used in the ion source to provide arsenic or phosphorus respectively for implantation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The ion source also has an indirectly heated cathode.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Alternatively this heated cathode can be used as one of the reflectors, eliminating the need for a dedicated one, or a directly heated cathode is used.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Oxygen-based gases (oxides) can be used to provide ions for implantation such as carbon dioxide for implanting carbon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Hydrogen or hydrogen with xenon, krypton or argon may be added to the plasma to delay the degradation of tungsten components due to the halogen cycle.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The hydrogen can come from a high pressure cylinder or from a hydrogen generator that uses electrolysis.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Repellers at each end of the ion source continually move the atoms from one end of the ion source to the other, resembling two mirrors pointed at each other constantly reflecting light.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In medium current ion implanters there is also a neutral ion trap before the process chamber to remove neutral ions from the ion beam.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Gallium, Selenium and Indium are often implanted from solid sources such as selenium dioxide for selenium although it can also be implanted from hydrogen selenide.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Crucibles often last 60–100 hours and prevent ion implanters from changing recipes or process parameters in less than 20–30 minutes.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] If the target surface is larger than the ion beam diameter and a uniform distribution of implanted dose is desired over the target surface, then some combination of beam scanning and wafer motion is used.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Finally, the implanted surface is coupled with some method for collecting the accumulated charge of the implanted ions so that the delivered dose can be measured in a continuous fashion and the implant process stopped at the desired dose level.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Semiconductor doping with boron, phosphorus, or arsenic is a common application of ion implantation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] When implanted in a semiconductor, each dopant atom can create a charge carrier in the semiconductor after annealing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Annealing is necessary after ion implantation to activate dopants and can be carried out using a tube or batch furnace, Rapid Thermal Processing, flash lamp anneal, laser anneal or other annealing techniques.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] A hole can be created for a p-type dopant, and an electron for an n-type dopant.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] This modifies the conductivity of the semiconductor in its vicinity.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The technique is used, for example, for adjusting the threshold voltage of a MOSFET.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation is practical due to the high sensitivity of semiconductor devices to foreign atoms, as ion implantation does not deposit large numbers of atoms.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Sometimes such as during the manufacturing of SiC devices, ion implantation is carried out while heating the SiC wafer to 500 °C.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] This is known as a hot implant and it is used to control damage to the surface of the semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Cryogenic implants (Cryo-implants) can have the same effect.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The energies used in doping often vary from 1 KeV to 3 MeV and it is not possible to build an ion implanter capable of providing ions at any energy due to physical limitations.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] To increase the throughput of ion implanters, efforts have been made to increase the current of the beam created by the implanter.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The beam can be scanned across the wafer magnetically, electrostatically, mechanically or with a combination of these techniques.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] A mass analyzer magnet is used to select the ions that will be implanted on the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation is also used in displays containing LTPS transistors.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation was developed as a method of producing the p-n junction of photovoltaic devices in the late 1970s and early 1980s, along with the use of pulsed-electron beam for rapid annealing, although pulsed-electron beam for rapid annealing has not to date been used for commercial production.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation is not used in most photovoltaic silicon cells, instead, thermal diffusion doping is used.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] One prominent method for preparing silicon on insulator (SOI) substrates from conventional silicon substrates is the *SIMOX* (separation by implantation of oxygen) process, wherein a buried high dose oxygen implant is converted to silicon oxide by a high temperature annealing process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Mesotaxy is the term for the growth of a crystallographically matching phase underneath the surface of the host crystal (compare to epitaxy, which is the growth of the matching phase on the surface of a substrate).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In this process, ions are implanted at a high enough energy and dose into a material to create a layer of a second phase, and the temperature is controlled so that the crystal structure of the target is not destroyed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The crystal orientation of the layer can be engineered to match that of the target, even though the exact crystal structure and lattice constant may be very different.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] For example, after the implantation of nickel ions into a silicon wafer, a layer of nickel silicide can be grown in which the crystal orientation of the silicide matches that of the silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Nitrogen or other ions can be implanted into a tool steel target (drill bits, for example).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The structural change caused by the implantation produces a surface compression in the steel, which prevents crack propagation and thus makes the material more resistant to fracture.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The chemical change can also make the tool more resistant to corrosion.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In some applications, for example prosthetic devices such as artificial joints, it is desired to have surfaces very resistant to both chemical corrosion and wear due to friction.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation is used in such cases to engineer the surfaces of such devices for more reliable performance.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] As in the case of tool steels, the surface modification caused by ion implantation includes both a surface compression which prevents crack propagation and an alloying of the surface to make it more chemically resistant to corrosion.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation can be used to achieve ion beam mixing, i.e. mixing up atoms of different elements at an interface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] This may be useful for achieving graded interfaces or strengthening adhesion between layers of immiscible materials.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion implantation may be used to induce nano-dimensional particles in oxides such as sapphire and silica.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Typical ion beam energies used to produce nanoparticles range from 50 to 150 keV, with ion fluences that range from 1016 to 1018 ions/cm2.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The table below summarizes some of the work that has been done in this field for a sapphire substrate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] A wide variety of nanoparticles can be formed, with size ranges from 1 nm on up to 20 nm and with compositions that can contain the implanted species, combinations of the implanted ion and substrate, or that are comprised solely from the cation associated with the substrate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Composite materials based on dielectrics such as sapphire that contain dispersed metal nanoparticles are promising materials for optoelectronics and nonlinear optics.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Each individual ion produces many point defects in the target crystal on impact such as vacancies and interstitials.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Vacancies are crystal lattice points unoccupied by an atom: in this case the ion collides with a target atom, resulting in transfer of a significant amount of energy to the target atom such that it leaves its crystal site.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] This target atom then itself becomes a projectile in the solid, and can cause successive collision events.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Interstitials result when such atoms (or the original ion itself) come to rest in the solid, but find no vacant space in the lattice to reside.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] These point defects can migrate and cluster with each other, resulting in dislocation loops and other defects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Different ion species, implantation dose, and energy can lead to different types of defects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Strain and local distortion will also appear as a result of the ion implantation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Because ion implantation causes unwanted damage to the crystal structure of the target, ion implantation processing is often followed by thermal annealing to restore the crystal structure, as the thermal treatment can provide extra energy to the lattice.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Some common annealing techniques include conventional furnace annealing, rapid thermal annealing (RTA), and laser annealing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] RTA and laser annealing have much shorter annealing times, significantly limiting the dopant diffusion, while furnace annealing can achieve better uniformity.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The amount of crystallographic damage can be enough to completely amorphize the surface of the target: i.e. it can become an amorphous solid (such a solid produced from a melt is called a glass).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In some cases, complete amorphization of a target is preferable to a highly defective crystal: An amorphized film can be regrown at a lower temperature than required to anneal a highly damaged crystal.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Amorphisation of the substrate can occur as a result of the beam damage.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Some of the collision events result in atoms being ejected (sputtered) from the surface, and thus ion implantation will slowly etch away a surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The effect is only appreciable for very large doses.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] If there is a crystallographic structure to the target, and especially in semiconductor substrates where the crystal structure is more open, particular crystallographic directions offer much lower stopping than other directions.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] The result is that the range of an ion can be much longer if the ion travels exactly along a particular direction, for example the <110> direction in silicon and other diamond cubic materials.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] This effect is called *ion channelling*, and, like all the channelling effects, is highly nonlinear, with small variations from perfect orientation resulting in extreme differences in implantation depth.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] For this reason, most implantation is carried out a few degrees off-axis, where tiny alignment errors will have more predictable effects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Ion channelling can be used directly in Rutherford backscattering and related techniques as an analytical method to determine the amount and depth profile of damage in crystalline thin film materials.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In fabricating wafers, toxic materials such as arsine and phosphine are often used in the ion implanter process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Other common carcinogenic, corrosive, flammable, or toxic elements include antimony, arsenic, phosphorus, and boron.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] Semiconductor fabrication facilities are highly automated, but residue of hazardous elements in machines can be encountered during servicing and in vacuum pump hardware.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] High voltage power supplies used in ion accelerators necessary for ion implantation can pose a risk of electrical injury.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In addition, high-energy atomic collisions can generate X-rays and, in some cases, other ionizing radiation and radionuclides.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/ion-implantation] In addition to high voltage, particle accelerators such as radio frequency linear particle accelerators and laser wakefield plasma accelerators present other hazards.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The fabrication process is performed in highly specialized semiconductor fabrication plants, also called foundries or "fabs", with the central part being the "clean room".
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In more advanced semiconductor devices, such as modern 14/10/7 nm nodes, fabrication can take up to 15 weeks, with 11–13 weeks being the industry average.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Production in advanced fabrication facilities is completely automated, with automated material handling systems taking care of the transport of wafers from machine to machine.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A wafer often has several integrated circuits, which are called dies as they are pieces diced from a single wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Individual dies are separated from a finished wafer in a process called die singulation, also called wafer dicing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The dies can then undergo further assembly and packaging.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Within fabrication plants, the wafers are transported inside special sealed plastic boxes called FOUPs.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] FOUPs in many fabs contain an internal nitrogen atmosphere which helps prevent copper from oxidizing on the wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Copper is used in modern semiconductors for wiring.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The insides of the processing equipment and FOUPs is kept cleaner than the surrounding air in the cleanroom.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This internal atmosphere is known as a mini-environment and helps improve yield, which is the number of working devices on a wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This mini environment is within an EFEM (equipment front end module) which allows a machine to receive FOUPs, and introduces wafers from the FOUPs into the machine.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Additionally, many machines also handle wafers in clean nitrogen or vacuum environments to reduce contamination and improve process control.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Fabrication plants need large amounts of liquid nitrogen to maintain the atmosphere inside production machinery and FOUPs, which are constantly purged with nitrogen.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] There can also be an air curtain or a mesh between the FOUP and the EFEM which helps reduce the amount of humidity that enters the FOUP and improves yield.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Some of the companies that manufacture machines used in the industrial semiconductor fabrication process include ASML, Applied Materials, Tokyo Electron, and Lam Research.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Feature size (or process size) is determined by the width of the smallest lines that can be patterned in a semiconductor fabrication process; this measurement is known as the linewidth.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Patterning often refers to photolithography which allows a device design or pattern to be defined on the device during fabrication.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] F2 is used as a measurement of area for different parts of a semiconductor device, based on the feature size of a semiconductor manufacturing process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Many semiconductor devices are designed in sections called cells, and each cell represents a small part of the device, such as a memory cell to store data.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Thus F2 is used to measure the area taken up by these cells or sections.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A specific **semiconductor process** has specific rules on the minimum size (width or CD/Critical Dimension) and spacing for features on each layer of the chip.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Normally, a new semiconductor process has smaller minimum sizes and tighter spacing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In some cases, this allows a simple die shrink of a currently produced chip design to reduce costs, improve performance, and increase transistor density (number of transistors per unit area) without the expense of a new design.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Early semiconductor processes had arbitrary names for generations (viz., HMOS I/II/III/IV and CHMOS III/III-E/IV/V).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Later each new generation process became known as a **technology node** or **process node**, designated by the process' **minimum feature size** in nanometers (or historically micrometers) of the process's transistor gate length, such as the "90 nm process".
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Initially transistor gate length was smaller than that suggested by the process node name (e.g.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] 350 nm node); however, this trend reversed in 2009.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Feature sizes can have no connection to the nanometers (nm) used in marketing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] For example, Intel's former 10 nm process actually has features (the tips of FinFET fins) with a width of 7 nm, so the Intel 10 nm process is similar in transistor density to TSMC's 7 nm process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As another example, GlobalFoundries' 12 and 14 nm processes have similar feature sizes.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1955, Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derick, working at Bell Telephone Laboratories, accidentally grew a layer of silicon dioxide over the silicon wafer, for which they observed surface passivation effects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] By 1957 Frosch and Derick, using masking and predeposition, were able to manufacture silicon dioxide transistors; the first planar field effect transistors, in which drain and source were adjacent at the same surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] At Bell Labs, the importance of their discoveries was immediately realized.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Memos describing the results of their work circulated at Bell Labs before being formally published in 1957.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] At Shockley Semiconductor, Shockley had circulated the preprint of their article in December 1956 to all his senior staff, including Jean Hoerni, who would later invent the planar process in 1959 while at Fairchild Semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1948, Bardeen patented an insulated-gate transistor (IGFET) with an inversion layer; Bardeen's concept forms the basis of MOSFET technology today.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] An improved type of MOSFET technology, CMOS, was developed by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] CMOS was commercialised by RCA in the late 1960s.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] RCA commercially used CMOS for its 4000-series integrated circuits in 1968, starting with a 20 μm process before gradually scaling to a 10 μm process over the next several years.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Many early semiconductor device manufacturers developed and built their own equipment such as ion implanters.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Manasevit was the first to document epitaxial growth of silicon on sapphire while working at the Autonetics division of North American Aviation (now Boeing).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1964, he published his findings with colleague William Simpson in the *Journal of Applied Physics*.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Robinson fabricated a MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor) using the silicon-on-sapphire process at RCA Laboratories.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Semiconductor device manufacturing has since spread from Texas and California in the 1960s to the rest of the world, including Asia, Europe, and the Middle East.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In the era of 2-inch wafers, these were handled manually using tweezers and held manually for the time required for a given process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Tweezers were replaced by vacuum wands as they generate fewer particles which can contaminate the wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Wafer carriers or cassettes, which can hold several wafers at once, were developed to carry several wafers between process steps.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] However, since wafers still had to be individually removed, processed, and returned, acid-resistant carriers were later introduced so the entire cassette could be dipped directly into wet etching and cleaning tanks, eliminating this time-consuming process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] When wafer sizes increased to 100 mm, the entire cassette would often not be dipped as uniformly, and the quality of the results across the wafer became hard to control.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] By the time 150 mm wafers arrived, the cassettes were not dipped and were only used as wafer carriers and holders to store wafers, and robotics became prevalent for handling wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] With 200 mm wafers, manual handling of wafer cassettes becomes risky as they are heavier.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In the 1970s and 1980s, several companies migrated their semiconductor manufacturing technology from bipolar to MOSFET technology.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Semiconductor manufacturing equipment has been considered costly since 1978.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1984, KLA developed the first automatic reticle and photomask inspection tool.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1985, KLA developed an automatic inspection tool for silicon wafers, which replaced manual microscope inspection.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1985, SGS (now STmicroelectronics) invented BCD, also called BCDMOS, a semiconductor manufacturing process using bipolar, CMOS and DMOS devices.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Applied Materials developed the first practical multi-chamber, or cluster wafer processing tool, the Precision 5000.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Until the 1980s, physical vapor deposition was the primary technique used for depositing materials onto wafers, until the advent of chemical vapor deposition.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Equipment with diffusion pumps was replaced with those using turbomolecular pumps, as the latter do not use oil, which often contaminates wafers during processing in vacuum.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] 200 mm diameter wafers were first used in 1990 and became the standard until the introduction of 300 mm diameter wafers in 2000.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Bridge tools were used in the transition from 150 mm wafers to 200 mm wafers and in the transition from 200 mm to 300 mm wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The semiconductor industry has adopted larger wafers to cope with the increased demand for chips as larger wafers provide more surface area per wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Over time, the industry shifted to 300 mm wafers which brought along the adoption of FOUPs, but many products that are not advanced are still produced in 200 mm wafers such as analog ICs, RF chips, power ICs, BCDMOS and MEMS devices.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Some processes such as cleaning, ion implantation, etching, annealing and oxidation started to adopt single wafer processing instead of batch wafer processing to improve the reproducibility of results.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A similar trend existed in MEMS manufacturing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The semiconductor industry is a global business today.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The leading semiconductor manufacturers typically have facilities all over the world.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Samsung Electronics, the world's largest manufacturer of semiconductors, has facilities in South Korea and the US.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Intel, the second-largest manufacturer, has facilities in Europe and Asia as well as the US.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] TSMC, the world's largest pure-play foundry, has facilities in Taiwan, China, Singapore, and the US.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Qualcomm and Broadcom are among the biggest fabless semiconductor companies, outsourcing their production to companies like TSMC.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] They also have facilities spread in different countries.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As the average utilization of semiconductor devices increased, durability became an issue and manufacturers started to design their devices to ensure they last for enough time, and this depends on the market the device is designed for.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This especially became a problem at the 10 nm node.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Silicon on insulator (SOI) technology has been used in AMD's 130 nm, 90 nm, 65 nm, 45 nm and 32 nm single, dual, quad, six and eight core processors made since 2001.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] During the transition from 200 mm to 300 mm wafers in 2001, many bridge tools were used which could process both 200 mm and 300 mm wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] At the time, 18 companies could manufacture chips in the leading edge 130 nm process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 2006, 450 mm wafers were expected to be adopted in 2012, and 675 mm wafers were expected to be used by 2021.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Since 2009, "node" has become a commercial name for marketing purposes that indicates new generations of process technologies, without any relation to gate length, metal pitch or gate pitch.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] For example, GlobalFoundries' 7 nm process was similar to Intel's 10 nm process, thus the conventional notion of a process node has become blurred.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Additionally, TSMC and Samsung's 10 nm processes are only slightly denser than Intel's 14 nm in transistor density.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] They are actually much closer to Intel's 14 nm process than they are to Intel's 10 nm process (e.g.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Samsung's 10 nm processes' fin pitch is the same as that of Intel's 14 nm process: 42 nm).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Intel has changed the name of its 10 nm process to position it as a 7 nm process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As transistors become smaller, new effects start to influence design decisions, such as self-heating of the transistors, and other effects, such as electromigration, have become more evident since the 16nm node.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A startup called SuVolta created a technology called Deeply Depleted Channel (DDC) to compete with FinFET transistors; it uses very lightly doped planar transistors at the 65 nm node.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] FD-SOI was seen as a potential low cost alternative to FinFETs.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As of 2019, 14 nm process and 10 nm process chips are in mass production by Intel, UMC, TSMC, Samsung, Micron, SK Hynix, Toshiba Memory and GlobalFoundries, with 7 nm process chips in mass production by TSMC and Samsung, although their 7 nm node definition is similar to Intel's 10 nm process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The 5 nm process began being produced by Samsung in 2018.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As of 2019, the node with the highest transistor density is TSMC's 5 nm N5 node, with a density of 171.3 million transistors per square millimeter.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 2019, Samsung and TSMC announced plans to produce 3 nm process nodes.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] GlobalFoundries has decided to stop the development of new nodes beyond 12 nm to save resources, as it has determined that setting up a new fab to handle sub-12 nm orders would be beyond the company's financial abilities.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] From 2020 to 2023, there was a global chip shortage.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] During this shortage caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, many semiconductor manufacturers banned employees from leaving company grounds.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Many countries granted subsidies to semiconductor companies for building new fabrication plants or fabs.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Many companies were affected by counterfeit chips.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Semiconductors have become vital to the world economy and the national security of some countries.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The US has asked TSMC to not produce semiconductors for Huawei, a Chinese company.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] CFET transistors were explored, which stacks NMOS and PMOS transistors on top of each other.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Two approaches were evaluated for constructing these transistors: a monolithic approach which built both types of transistors in one process, and a sequential approach which built the two types of transistors separately and then stacked them.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Equipment for carrying out these processes is made by a handful of companies.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] All equipment needs to be tested before a semiconductor fabrication plant is started.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] These processes are done after integrated circuit design.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A semiconductor fab operates 24/7 and many fabs use large amounts of water, primarily for rinsing the chips.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Additionally, steps such as Wright etch may be carried out.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] When feature widths were far greater than about 10 micrometres, semiconductor purity was not as big of an issue as it is today in device manufacturing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In the 1960s, workers could work on semiconductor devices in street clothing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As devices become more integrated, cleanrooms must become even cleaner.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Today, fabrication plants are pressurized with filtered air to remove even the smallest particles, which could come to rest on the wafers and contribute to defects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The FFUs, combined with raised floors with grills, help ensure a laminar air flow, to ensure that particles are immediately brought down to the floor and do not stay suspended in the air due to turbulence.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The workers in a semiconductor fabrication facility are required to wear cleanroom suits to protect the devices from contamination by humans.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] To increase yield, FOUPs and semiconductor capital equipment may have a mini environment with ISO class 1 level of dust, and FOUPs can have an even cleaner micro environment.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] FOUPs and SMIF pods isolate the wafers from the air in the cleanroom, increasing yield because they reduce the number of defects caused by dust particles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Also, fabs have as few people as possible in the cleanroom to make maintaining the cleanroom environment easier, since people, even when wearing cleanroom suits, shed large amounts of particles, especially when walking.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A typical wafer is made out of extremely pure silicon that is grown into mono-crystalline cylindrical ingots (boules) up to 300 mm (slightly less than 12 inches) in diameter using the Czochralski process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] These ingots are then sliced into wafers about 0.75 mm thick and polished to obtain a very regular and flat surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] During the production process wafers are often grouped into lots, which are represented by a FOUP, SMIF or a wafer cassette, which are wafer carriers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] FOUPs and SMIFs can be transported in the fab between machines and equipment with an automated OHT (Overhead Hoist Transport) AMHS (Automated Material Handling System).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Besides SMIFs and FOUPs, wafer cassettes can be placed in a wafer box or a wafer carrying box.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In semiconductor device fabrication, the various processing steps fall into four general categories: deposition, removal, patterning, and modification of electrical properties.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Modification of electrical properties now also extends to the reduction of a material's dielectric constant in low-κ insulators via exposure to ultraviolet light in UV processing (UVP).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Modification is frequently achieved by oxidation, which can be carried out to create semiconductor-insulator junctions, such as in the local oxidation of silicon (LOCOS) to fabricate metal oxide field effect transistors.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Modern chips have up to eleven or more metal levels produced in over 300 or more sequenced processing steps.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A recipe in semiconductor manufacturing is a list of conditions under which a wafer will be processed by a particular machine in a processing step during manufacturing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Process variability is a challenge in semiconductor processing, in which wafers are not processed evenly or the quality or effectiveness of processes carried out on a wafer are not even across the wafer surface.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Wafer processing is separated into FEOL and BEOL stages.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] FEOL processing refers to the formation of the transistors directly in the silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The raw wafer is engineered by the growth of an ultrapure, virtually defect-free silicon layer through epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In the most advanced logic devices, *prior* to the silicon epitaxy step, tricks are performed to improve the performance of the transistors to be built.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] One method involves introducing a *straining step* wherein a silicon variant such as silicon-germanium (SiGe) is deposited.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Once the epitaxial silicon is deposited, the crystal lattice becomes stretched somewhat, resulting in improved electronic mobility.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Another method, called *silicon on insulator* technology, involves the insertion of an insulating layer between the raw silicon wafer and the thin layer of subsequent silicon epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This method results in the creation of transistors with reduced parasitic effects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Semiconductor equipment may have several chambers that process wafers in processes such as deposition and etching.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Many pieces of equipment handle wafers between these chambers in an internal nitrogen or vacuum environment to improve process control.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Wet benches with tanks containing chemical solutions were historically used for cleaning and etching wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] At the 90nm node, transistor channels made with strain engineering were introduced to improve drive current in PMOS transistors by introducing regions with Silicon-Germanium in the transistor.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The same was done in NMOS transistors at the 20nm node.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 2007, HKMG (high-k/metal gate) transistors were introduced by Intel at the 45 nm node, which replaced polysilicon gates which in turn replaced metal gate (aluminum gate) technology in the 1970s.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] High-k dielectric such as hafnium oxide (HfO2) replaced silicon oxynitride (SiON), to prevent large amounts of leakage current in the transistor while allowing for continued scaling or shrinking of the transistors.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] However, HfO2 is not compatible with polysilicon gates; it requires the use of a metal gate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Two approaches were used in production: gate-first and gate-last.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In DRAM memories this technology was first adopted in 2015.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A third process, full silicidation (FUSI) was not pursued due to manufacturing problems.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Gate-first became dominant at the 22nm/20nm node.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] HKMG has been extended from planar transistors for use in FinFET and nanosheet transistors.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Hafnium silicon oxynitride can also be used instead of Hafnium oxide.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Since the 16 nm/14 nm node, Atomic layer etching (ALE) is increasingly used for etching as it offers higher precision than other etching methods.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In production, plasma ALE is commonly used, which removes materials unidirectionally, creating structures with vertical walls.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Thermal ALE can also be used to remove materials isotropically, in all directions at the same time but without the capability to create vertical walls.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Plasma ALE was initially adopted for etching contacts in transistors, and since the 7nm node it is also used to create transistor structures by etching them.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Front-end surface engineering is followed by growth of the gate dielectric (traditionally silicon dioxide), patterning of the gate, patterning of the source and drain regions, and subsequent implantation or diffusion of dopants to obtain the desired complementary electrical properties.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) devices, storage capacitors are also fabricated at this time, typically stacked above the access transistor (the now defunct DRAM manufacturer Qimonda implemented these capacitors with trenches etched deep into the silicon surface).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Once the various semiconductor devices have been created, they must be interconnected to form the desired electrical circuits.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This occurs in a series of wafer processing steps collectively referred to as BEOL (not to be confused with *back end* of chip fabrication, which refers to the packaging and testing stages).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] BEOL processing involves creating metal interconnecting wires that are isolated by dielectric layers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] BEoL has been used since 1995 at the 350 nm and 250 nm nodes (0.35 and 0.25 micron nodes), at the same time, chemical mechanical polishing began to be employed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] At the time, 2 metal layers for interconnect, also called metallization was state-of-the-art.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Since the 22nm node, some manufacturers have added a new process called middle-of-line (MOL) which connects the transistors to the rest of the interconnect made in the BEoL process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The MOL is often based on tungsten and has upper and lower layers: the lower layer connects the junctions of the transistors, and an upper layer which is a tungsten plug that connects the transistors to the interconnect.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Intel at the 10nm node introduced contact-over-active-gate (COAG) which, instead of placing the contact for connecting the transistor close to the gate of the transistor, places it directly over the gate of the transistor to improve transistor density.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Historically, the metal wires have been composed **of aluminum**.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In this approach to wiring (often called *subtractive aluminum*), blanket films of aluminum are deposited first, patterned, and then etched, leaving isolated wires.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Dielectric material is then deposited over the exposed wires.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The aluminum was sometimes alloyed with copper for preventing recrystallization.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Gold was also used in interconnects in early chips.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This performance enhancement also comes at a reduced cost via damascene processing, which eliminates processing steps.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As the number of interconnect levels increases, planarization of the previous layers is required to ensure a flat surface prior to subsequent lithography.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Without it, the levels would become increasingly crooked, extending outside the depth of focus of available lithography, and thus interfering with the ability to pattern.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] CMP (chemical-mechanical planarization) is the primary processing method to achieve such planarization, although dry *etch back* is still sometimes employed when the number of interconnect levels is no more than three.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Copper interconnects use an electrically conductive barrier layer to prevent the copper from diffusing into ("poisoning") its surroundings, often made of tantalum nitride.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 1997, IBM was the first to adopt copper interconnects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In 2014, Applied Materials proposed the use of cobalt in interconnects at the 22nm node, used for encapsulating copper interconnects in cobalt to prevent electromigration, replacing tantalum nitride since it needs to be thicker than cobalt in this application.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The highly serialized nature of wafer processing has increased the demand for metrology in between the various processing steps.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] For example, thin film metrology based on ellipsometry or reflectometry is used to tightly control the thickness of gate oxide, as well as the thickness, refractive index, and extinction coefficient of photoresist and other coatings.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Wafer metrology equipment/tools, or wafer inspection tools are used to verify that the wafers haven't been damaged by previous processing steps up until testing; if too many dies on one wafer have failed, the entire wafer is scrapped to avoid the costs of further processing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Virtual metrology has been used to predict wafer properties based on statistical methods without performing the physical measurement itself.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Once the front-end process has been completed, the semiconductor devices or chips are subjected to a variety of electrical tests to determine if they function properly.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The percent of devices on the wafer found to perform properly is referred to as the **yield**.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Manufacturers are typically secretive about their yields, but it can be as low as 30%, meaning that only 30% of the chips on the wafer work as intended.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Process variation is one among many reasons for low yield.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Testing is carried out to prevent faulty chips from being assembled into relatively expensive packages.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The yield is often but not necessarily related to device (die or chip) size.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] As an example, in December 2019, TSMC announced an average yield of ~80%, with a peak yield per wafer of >90% for their 5nm test chips with a die size of 17.92 mm2.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The yield went down to 32% with an increase in die size to 100 mm2.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The number of killer defects on a wafer, regardless of die size, can be noted as the defect density (or D0) of the wafer per unit area, usually cm2.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The fab tests the chips on the wafer with an electronic tester that presses tiny probes against the chip.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The machine marks each bad chip with a drop of dye.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The resulting binning data can be graphed, or logged, on a wafer map to trace manufacturing defects and mark bad chips.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This map can also be used during wafer assembly and packaging.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Chips may have spare parts to allow the chip to fully pass testing even if it has several non-working parts.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Chips are also tested again after packaging, as the bond wires may be missing, or analog performance may be altered by the package.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] This is referred to as the "final test".
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Usually, the fab charges for testing time, with prices on the order of cents per second.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Testing times vary from a few milliseconds to a couple of seconds, and the test software is optimized for reduced testing time.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Multiple chip (multi-site) testing is also possible because many testers have the resources to perform most or all of the tests in parallel and on several chips at once.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Chips are often designed with "testability features" such as scan chains or a "built-in self-test" to speed testing and reduce testing costs.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In certain designs that use specialized analog fab processes, wafers are also laser-trimmed during testing, in order to achieve tightly distributed resistance values as specified by the design.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Good designs try to test and statistically manage *corners* (extremes of silicon behavior caused by a high operating temperature combined with the extremes of fab processing steps).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Most designs cope with at least 64 corners.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Device yield or die yield is the number of working chips or dies on a wafer, given in percentage since the number of chips on a wafer (Die per wafer, DPW) can vary depending on the chips' size and the wafer's diameter.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Dust particles have an increasing effect on yield as feature sizes are shrunk with newer processes.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Automation and the use of mini environments inside of production equipment, FOUPs and SMIFs have enabled a reduction in defects caused by dust particles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Device yield must be kept high to reduce the selling price of the working chips since working chips have to pay for those chips that failed, and to reduce the cost of wafer processing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Yield can also be affected by the design and operation of the fab.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Tight control over contaminants and the production process are necessary to increase yield.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Contaminants may be chemical contaminants or be dust particles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] "Killer defects" are those caused by dust particles that cause complete failure of the device (such as a transistor).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A particle needs to be 1/5 the size of a feature to cause a killer defect.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] So if a feature is 100 nm across, a particle only needs to be 20 nm across to cause a killer defect.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Electrostatic electricity can also affect yield adversely.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Chemical contaminants or impurities include heavy metals such as iron, copper, nickel, zinc, chromium, gold, mercury and silver, alkali metals such as sodium, potassium and lithium, and elements such as aluminum, magnesium, calcium, chlorine, sulfur, carbon, and fluorine.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] It is important for these elements to not remain in contact with the silicon, as they could reduce yield.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Chemical mixtures may be used to remove these elements from the silicon; different mixtures are effective against different elements.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Several models are used to estimate yield.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] They are Murphy's model, Poisson's model, the binomial model, Moore's model and Seeds' model.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] There is no universal model; a model has to be chosen based on actual yield distribution (the location of defective chips).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Smaller dies cost less to produce (since more fit on a wafer, and wafers are processed and priced as a whole), and can help achieve higher yields since smaller dies have a lower chance of having a defect, due to their lower surface area on the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] However, smaller dies require smaller features to achieve the same functions of larger dies or surpass them, and smaller features require reduced process variation and increased purity (reduced contamination) to maintain high yields.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Metrology tools are used to inspect the wafers during the production process and predict yield, so wafers predicted to have too many defects may be scrapped to save on processing costs.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Once tested, a wafer is typically reduced in thickness in a process also known as "backlap", "backfinish", "wafer backgrind" or "wafer thinning" before the wafer is scored and then broken into individual dies, a process known as wafer dicing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Only the good, unmarked chips are packaged.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] After the dies are tested for functionality and binned, they are packaged.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Plastic or ceramic packaging involves mounting the die, connecting the die/bond pads to the pins on the package, and sealing the die.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Tiny bondwires are used to connect the pads to the pins.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] In the 'old days' (1970s), wires were attached by hand, but now specialized machines perform the task.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Traditionally, these wires have been composed of gold, leading to a lead frame (pronounced "leed frame") of solder-plated copper; lead is poisonous, so lead-free "lead frames" are now mandated by RoHS.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Traditionally the bond pads are located on the edges of the die, however, Flip-chip packaging can be used to place bond pads across the entire surface of the die.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Chip scale package (CSP) is another packaging technology.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A plastic dual in-line package, like most packages, is many times larger than the actual die hidden inside, whereas CSP chips are nearly the size of the die; a CSP can be constructed for each die *before* the wafer is diced.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The packaged chips are retested to ensure that they were not damaged during packaging and that the die-to-pin interconnect operation was performed correctly.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A laser then etches the chip's name and numbers on the package.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] A foundry is a company or fab performing manufacturing processes such as photolithography and etching that are part of the front end of semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Many toxic materials are used in the fabrication process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] It is vital that workers not be directly exposed to these dangerous substances.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] The high degree of automation common in the IC fabrication industry helps to reduce the risks of exposure.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-device-fabrication] Most fabrication facilities employ exhaust management systems, such as wet scrubbers, combustors, heated absorber cartridges, etc., to control the risk to workers and to the environment.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In the microelectronics industry, a **semiconductor fabrication plant**, also called a ***fab*** or a ***foundry***, is a factory where integrated circuits (ICs) are manufactured.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The *cleanroom* is where all fabrication takes place and contains the machinery for integrated circuit production such as steppers and/or scanners for photolithography, etching, cleaning, and doping.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Prices for pieces of equipment for the processing of 300mm wafers range to upwards of $4 million each with a few pieces of equipment reaching as high as $340 million (e.g.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] A typical fab will have several hundred equipment items.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Semiconductor fabrication requires many expensive devices.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Estimates put the cost of building a new fab at over one billion U.S. dollars with values as high as tens of billions of dollars not being uncommon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] For example, TSMC invested over $45 billion into a new fab for their 2nm process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] A foundry model emerged in the 1990s: Companies owning fabs that produced their own designs were known as *integrated device manufacturers* (IDMs).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Companies that outsourced manufacturing of their designs were termed *fabless semiconductor companies*.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Those foundries which did not create their own designs were called *pure-play semiconductor foundries*.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In the cleanroom, the environment is controlled to eliminate all dust, since even a single speck can ruin a microcircuit, which has nanoscale features much smaller than dust particles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The clean room must also be damped against vibration to enable nanometer-scale alignment of photolithography machines and must be kept within narrow bands of temperature and humidity.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Vibration control may be achieved by using deep piles in the cleanroom's foundation that anchor the cleanroom to the bedrock, careful selection of the construction site, and/or using vibration dampers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Controlling temperature and humidity is critical for minimizing static electricity.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Corona discharge sources can also be used to reduce static electricity.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Typically, an advance in chip-making technology requires a completely new fab to be built.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In the past, the equipment to outfit a fab was not very expensive and there were a huge number of smaller fabs producing chips in small quantities.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] However, the cost of the most up-to-date equipment has since grown to the point where a new fab can cost several billion dollars.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Another side effect of the cost has been the challenge to make use of older fabs.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] For many companies these older fabs are useful for producing designs for unique markets, such as embedded processors, flash memory, and microcontrollers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] However, for companies with more limited product lines, it is often best to either rent out the fab, or close it entirely.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] This is due to the tendency of the cost of upgrading an existing fab to produce devices requiring newer technology to exceed the cost of a completely new fab.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] There has been a trend to produce ever larger wafers; each process step is being performed on more and more chips at once.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The goal is to spread production costs (chemicals, fab time) over a larger number of sale-able chips.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] It is impossible (or at least impracticable) to retrofit machinery to handle larger wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] This is not to say that foundries using smaller wafers are necessarily obsolete; older foundries can be cheaper to operate, have higher yields for simple chips and still be productive.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The industry was aiming to move from the state-of-the-art wafer size 300 mm (12 in) to 450 mm by 2018.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In March 2014, Intel expected 450 mm deployment by 2020.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] But in 2016, corresponding joint research efforts were stopped.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Additionally, there is a large push to completely automate the production of semiconductor chips from beginning to end.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] This is often referred to as the "lights-out fab" concept.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The ultimate goal of process simulation is an accurate prediction of the active dopant distribution, the stress distribution and the device geometry.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation is typically used as an input for device simulation, the modeling of device electrical characteristics.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Collectively process and device simulation form the core tools for the design phase known as technology computer aided design (TCAD).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Considering the integrated circuit design process as a series of steps with decreasing levels of abstraction, logic synthesis would be at the highest level and TCAD, being closest to fabrication, would be the phase with the least amount of abstraction.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Because of the detailed physical modeling involved, process simulation is almost exclusively used to aid in the development of single devices whether discrete or as a part of an integrated circuit.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The fabrication of integrated circuit devices requires a series of processing steps called a process flow.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation involves modeling all essential steps in the process flow in order to obtain dopant and stress profiles and, to a lesser extent, device geometry.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The input for process simulation is the process flow and a layout.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The layout is selected as a linear cut in a full layout for a 2D simulation or a rectangular cut from the layout for a 3D simulation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] TCAD has traditionally focused mainly on the transistor fabrication part of the process flow ending with the formation of source and drain contacts—also known as front end of line manufacturing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Back end of line manufacturing, e.g. interconnect and dielectric layers are not considered.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] One reason for delineation is the availability of powerful analysis tools such as electron microscopy techniques, scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM), which allow for accurate measurement of device geometry.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] There are no similar tools available for accurate high resolution measurement of dopant or stress profiles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Nevertheless, there is growing interest to investigate the interaction between front end and back end manufacturing steps.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] For example, back end manufacturing may cause stress in the transistor region changing device performance.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] These interactions will stimulate the need for better interfaces to back end simulation tools or lead to integration of some of those capabilities into TCAD tools.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] In addition to the recent expanding scope of process simulation, there has always been a desire to have more accurate simulations.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] However, simplified physical models have been most commonly used in order to minimize computation time.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] But, shrinking device dimensions put increasing demands on the accuracy of dopant and stress profiles so new process models are added for each generation of devices to match new accuracy demands.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Many of the models were conceived by researchers long before they were needed, but sometimes new effects are only recognized and understood once process engineers discover a problem and experiments are performed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] In any case, the trend of adding more physical models and considering more detailed physical effects will continue and may accelerate.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The history of commercial process simulators began with the development of the Stanford University Process Engineering Models (SUPREM) program.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] SUPREM was the resulting software from research by Stanford professor Robert Dutton (engineer).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Building upon this beginning with improved models SUPREM II and SUPREM III were developed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] (TMA) was co-founded by Robert Dutton (engineer) in 1979.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] TMA was the first company to commercialize SUPREM III.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Later Silvaco also commercialized SUPREM and named the product ATHENA.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] TMA commercialized SUPREM-IV (2D version) and called it TSUPREM4.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] In 1992, Integrated Systems Engineering (ISE) came out with the 1D process simulator TESIM and the 2D process simulator DIOS.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] At about the same time development of a new 3D process and device simulator began at TMA and after TMA was acquired by Avanti, the product was released in 1998 as Taurus.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Around 1994 a first version of the Florida Object Oriented Process Simulator (FLOOPS) was completed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] FLOOPS was later commercialized by ISE in 2002.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] One other process simulator PROPHET was created around 1994 at Bell labs which later became Agere, but has not been sold commercially.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] In 2002 Synopsys acquired Avant!, corp. and in 2004 Synopsys acquired ISE.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Synopsys combined the features of Taurus and TSUPREM4, into the FLOOPS platform and called it Sentaurus Process.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Current Silvaco products are Victory Process and Victory Device for 2D/3D simulation, and legacy products Athena for 2D process simulation, and Atlas for 2D device simulation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] In 2013, Coventor released SEMulator3D, an advanced process simulator based upon voxel modeling and surface evolution.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Besides these simulators, there are numerous other university and commercial simulators such as PROMIS, PREDICT, PROSIM, ICECREM, DADOS, TITAN, MicroTec, DOPDEES, ALAMODE.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The process steps most often associated with process simulation are ion implantation, annealing (diffusion and dopant activation), etch, deposition, oxidation, and epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Other common steps include chemical-mechanical planarization (CMP), silicidation, and reflow.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] All commercial process simulators use a combination of the finite element analysis (FE) and/or finite volume methods (FV) methods.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] A complete description of FE/FV method is out of the scope of this article but there are many fine books which describe the topic thoroughly.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] However, it is important to discuss requirements for process simulation for achieving accurate results.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] These requirements are based on the same requirements as generic to FE/FV techniques with an additional difficulty coming from the changes in the geometry during the simulated fabrication of the device.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation uses an FE/FV mesh to compute and store the dopant and stress profiles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Each geometrical change in the simulation domain requires a new mesh which fits to the new boundaries.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] As will be described below, the large number of geometry modifying steps involved and the nature of process simulation where each step depends on the cumulative results of all previous steps, make process simulation an especially challenging application of the FE/FV technique.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] One of the most important results of process simulation is the dopant profile after processing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The accuracy of the profile strongly depends on maintaining a proper density of mesh points at any time during the simulation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The density of points should be just enough to resolve all dopant and defect profiles but not more because the computation expense of solving the diffusion equations increases with the number of mesh points.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] A typical full flow CMOS process simulation can have more than 50 mesh changes and the number of mesh changes can increase dramatically if adaptive meshing is performed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] For each mesh change, interpolation is used to obtain data values on the new mesh.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] It is important to manage the mesh changes in such a way to avoid accuracy degradation due to interpolation error.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] The easiest way to do this is to always keep points once they are introduced into the mesh, but this has the drawback of producing very many mesh points which can be computationally expensive.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Maintaining a balance between interpolation error, computational expense, and minimization of required user input is important for obtaining accurate results with a minimum of computational expense.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] This is especially true when simulating devices in 3D.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Without careful placement of mesh either the accuracy will suffer unacceptably, or the computational expense will be too great to be useful.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation tools so far have had limited success in completely automating mesh adaptation such that no user intervention is required.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] This places a requirement of the user to understand meshing and how it affects simulation accuracy and run time and the burdens the user to track mesh changes during the simulation to ensure proper mesh is maintained.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] One of the most important uses of TCAD tools is to explore new device technology where many exploratory simulations are performed in order to give the device designer a better understanding of possible benefits as well as drawbacks of a specific technology.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] This use case demands sequential simulations with some analysis in between.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] In order to be useful, many simulation cycles must be run within the time allotted for exploration, putting a high priority on minimization of simulation run time.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Currently, full flow standard CMOS simulations are most often accomplished with a combination of 1D and 2D simulation and take less than a few hours on a 2.6 GHz Pentium 4.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] To perform these simulations in 3D (from gate formation on) would take a minimum of 24 hours for minimum accuracy simulation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] Most of the information desired from TCAD simulations can be extracted from the simplification that the device can be treated uniformly in depth (i.e. a 2D simulation).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/semiconductor-process-simulation] To include the effects device shape along the depth or to investigate implant shadowing, 3D simulations must be performed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In electronics, a **wafer** (also called a **slice** or **substrate**) is a thin slice of semiconductor, such as a crystalline silicon (c-Si, silicium), used for the fabrication of integrated circuits and, in photovoltaics, to manufacture solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The wafer serves as the substrate for microelectronic devices built in and upon the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] It undergoes many microfabrication processes, such as doping, ion implantation, etching, thin-film deposition of various materials, and photolithographic patterning.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Finally, the individual microcircuits are separated by wafer dicing and packaged as an integrated circuit.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In the semiconductor industry, the term wafer appeared in the 1950s to describe a thin round slice of semiconductor material, typically germanium or silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The round shape characteristic of these wafers comes from single-crystal ingots usually produced using the Czochralski method.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Though, silicon wafers were first introduced in the 1940s.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] By 1960, silicon wafers were being manufactured in the U.S. by companies such as MEMC and SunEdison.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Hurd, and Gerard Seeley, while working under IBM, filed Patent US3423629A for the first high-capacity epitaxial apparatus.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafers are formed of highly pure, nearly defect-free single crystalline material, with a purity of 99.9999999% (9N) or higher.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] One process for forming crystalline wafers is known as the Czochralski method, invented by Polish chemist Jan Czochralski.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In this process, a cylindrical ingot of high purity monocrystalline semiconductor, such as silicon or germanium, called a boule, is formed by pulling a seed crystal from a melt.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Donor impurity atoms, such as boron or phosphorus in the case of silicon, can be added to the molten intrinsic material in precise amounts in order to dope the crystal, thus changing it into an extrinsic semiconductor of n-type or p-type.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The boule is then sliced with a wafer saw (a type of wire saw), machined to improve flatness, chemically etched to remove crystal damage from machining steps and finally polished to form wafers.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The size of wafers for photovoltaics is 100–200 mm square and the thickness is 100–500 μm.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Electronics use wafer sizes from 100 to 450 mm diameter.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The largest wafers made have a diameter of 450 mm, but are not yet in general use.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafers are cleaned with weak acids to remove unwanted particles.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] There are several standard cleaning procedures to make sure the surface of a silicon wafer contains no contamination.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] One of the most effective methods is the RCA clean.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] When used for solar cells, the wafers are textured to create a rough surface to increase surface area and so their efficiency.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The generated PSG (phosphosilicate glass) is removed from the edge of the wafer in the etching.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Silicon wafers are available in a variety of diameters from 25.4 mm (1 inch) to 300 mm (11.8 inches).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Semiconductor fabrication plants, colloquially known as *fabs*, are defined by the diameter of wafers that they are tooled to produce.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The diameter has gradually increased to improve throughput and reduce cost with the current state-of-the-art fab using 300 mm, with a proposal to adopt 450 mm.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Intel, TSMC, and Samsung were separately conducting research to the advent of 450 mm "prototype" (research) fabs, though serious hurdles remain.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafers grown using materials other than silicon will have different thicknesses than a silicon wafer of the same diameter.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafer thickness is determined by the mechanical strength of the material used; the wafer must be thick enough to support its own weight without cracking during handling.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The tabulated thicknesses relate to when that process was introduced, and are not necessarily correct currently, for example the IBM BiCMOS7WL process is on 8-inch wafers, but these are only 200 μm thick.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The weight of the wafer increases with its thickness and the square of its diameter.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Date of introduction does not indicate that factories will convert their equipment immediately, in fact, many factories do not bother upgrading.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Instead, companies tend to expand and build whole new lines with newer technologies, leaving a large spectrum of technologies in use at the same time.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] GaN substrate wafers typically have had their own independent timelines, parallel but far lagging silicon substrate, but ahead of other substrates.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The world's first 300 mm wafer made of GaN was announced in Sept 2024 by Infineon, suggesting in the coming future they could put into use the first factory with 300 mm GaN commercial output.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Meanwhile world's first Silicon Carbide (SiC) 200 mm wafers were announced in July 2021 by ST Microelectronics.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] It is not known if SiC 200 mm has entered volume production as of 2024, as typically the largest fabs for SiC in commercial production remain at 150 mm.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Silicon on sapphire (SOS) is a specific type of Silicon on Insulator (SOI) technology, where the insulating substrate is sapphire and the active superstrate is silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Epitaxial layers and doping can be tailored as needed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] SOS in commercial production is typically maxed out at 150 mm wafer sizes as of 2024.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] GaAs wafers tend to be 150 mm at largest, in commercial production as of 2024.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] AlN tends to be 50 mm or 2 inch wafers in commercial production, while 100 mm or 4 inch wafers are being developed as of 2024 by wafer suppliers like Asahi Kasei.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] However, merely because a wafer exists commercially, does not imply in any way that processing equipment to produce chips on that wafer exists, indeed such equipment tends to lag development until paying end customer demand materializes.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Even after equipment is developed (years), it can take further years for fabs to figure out how to use the machines productively.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Diamond tends to be 50-55 mm or ~2 inch wafers in prototype production, while commercial production is being targeted as of 2026.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] A unit of wafer fabrication step, such as an etch step, can produce more chips proportional to the increase in wafer area, while the cost of the unit fabrication step goes up more slowly than the wafer area.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] This was the cost basis for increasing wafer size.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Conversion to 300 mm wafers from 200 mm wafers began in early 2000, and reduced the price per die for about 30–40%.Larger diameter wafers allow for more die per wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] M1 wafer size (156.75 mm) is in the process of being phased out in China as of 2020.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Various nonstandard wafer sizes have arisen, so efforts to fully adopt the M10 standard (182 mm) are ongoing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Like other semiconductor fabrication processes, driving down costs has been the main driving factor for this attempted size increase, in spite of the differences in the manufacturing processes of different types of devices.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafers are grown from crystal having a regular crystal structure, with silicon having a diamond cubic structure with a lattice spacing of 5.430710 Å (0.5430710 nm).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] When cut into wafers, the surface is aligned in one of several relative directions known as crystal orientations.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Orientation is defined by the Miller index with (100) or (111) faces being the most common for silicon.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Orientation is important since many of a single crystal's structural and electronic properties are highly anisotropic.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Ion implantation depths depend on the wafer's crystal orientation, since each direction offers distinct paths for transport.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafer cleavage typically occurs only in a few well-defined directions.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Scoring the wafer along cleavage planes allows it to be easily diced into individual chips ("dies") so that the billions of individual circuit elements on an average wafer can be separated into many individual circuits.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafers under 200 mm diameter have *flats* cut into one or more sides indicating the crystallographic planes of the wafer (usually a {110} face).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In earlier-generation wafers a pair of flats at different angles additionally conveyed the doping type (see illustration for conventions).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Wafers of 200 mm diameter and above use a single small notch to convey wafer orientation, with no visual indication of doping type.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] 450 mm wafers are notchless, relying on a laser scribed structure on the wafer surface for orientation.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Silicon wafers are generally not 100% pure silicon, but are instead formed with an initial impurity doping concentration between 1013 and 1016 atoms per cm3 of boron, phosphorus, arsenic, or antimony which is added to the melt and defines the wafer as either bulk n-type or p-type.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] However, compared with single-crystal silicon's atomic density of 5×1022 atoms per cm3, this still gives a purity greater than 99.9999%.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The wafers can also be initially provided with some interstitial oxygen concentration.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Carbon and metallic contamination are kept to a minimum.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Transition metals, in particular, must be kept below parts per billion concentrations for electronic applications.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] There is considerable resistance to the 450 mm transition despite the possible productivity improvement, because of concern about insufficient return on investment.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] There are also issues related to increased inter-die / edge-to-edge wafer variation and additional edge defects.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] 450mm wafers are expected to cost 4 times as much as 300mm wafers, and equipment costs are expected to rise by 20 to 50%.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Higher cost semiconductor fabrication equipment for larger wafers increases the cost of 450 mm fabs (semiconductor fabrication facilities or factories).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Lithographer Chris Mack claimed in 2012 that the overall price per die for 450 mm wafers would be reduced by only 10–20% compared to 300 mm wafers, because over 50% of total wafer processing costs are lithography-related.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Converting to larger 450 mm wafers would reduce price per die only for process operations such as etch where cost is related to wafer count, not wafer area.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Cost for processes such as lithography is proportional to wafer area, and larger wafers would not reduce the lithography contribution to die cost.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Nikon planned to deliver 450-mm lithography equipment in 2015, with volume production in 2017.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In November 2013 ASML paused development of 450-mm lithography equipment, citing uncertain timing of chipmaker demand.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In the mid of 2014 CNSE has announced that it will reveal first fully patterned 450mm wafers at SEMICON West.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In early 2017, the G450C began to dismantle its activities over 450mm wafer research due to undisclosed reasons.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Various sources have speculated that demise of the group came after charges of bid rigging made against Alain E.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Kaloyeros, who at the time was a chief executive at the SUNY Poly.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The industry realization of the fact that the 300mm manufacturing optimization is more cheap than costly 450mm transition may also have played a role.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] The timeline for 450 mm has not been fixed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In 2012, it was expected that 450mm production would start in 2017, which never realized.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Mark Durcan, then CEO of Micron Technology, said in February 2014 that he expects 450 mm adoption to be delayed indefinitely or discontinued.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] "I am not convinced that 450mm will ever happen but, to the extent that it does, it's a long way out in the future.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] "There is a lot of investment that needs to go on in the equipment community to make that happen.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] And the value at the end of the day – so that customers would buy that equipment – I think is dubious." As of March 2014, Intel Corporation expected 450 mm deployment by 2020 (by the end of this decade).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Mark LaPedus of semiengineering.com reported in mid-2014 that chipmakers had delayed adoption of 450 mm "for the foreseeable future." According to this report some observers expected 2018 to 2020, while G.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Dan Hutcheson, chief executive of VLSI Research, didn't see 450mm fabs moving into production until 2020 to 2025.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] 300mm FOUPs have handles so that they can be still be moved by hand.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] 450mm FOUPs weigh 45 kilograms when loaded with 25 450 mm wafers, thus cranes are necessary to manually handle the FOUPs and handles are no longer present in the FOUP.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] FOUPs are moved around using material handling systems from Muratec or Daifuku.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] These major investments were undertaken in the economic downturn following the dot-com bubble, resulting in huge resistance to upgrading to 450 mm by the original timeframe.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] On the ramp-up to 450 mm, the crystal ingots will be 3 times heavier (total weight a metric ton) and take 2–4 times longer to cool, and the process time will be double.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] All told, the development of 450 mm wafers requires significant engineering, time, and cost to overcome.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In order to minimize the cost per die, manufacturers wish to maximize the number of dies that can be made from a single wafer; dies always have a square or rectangular shape due to the constraint of wafer dicing.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Note that formulas estimating the gross dies per wafer (**DPW**) account only for the number of complete dies that can fit on the wafer; gross DPW calculations do *not* account for yield loss among those complete dies due to defects or parametric issues.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] This formula simply states that the number of dies which can fit on the wafer cannot exceed the area of the wafer divided by the area of each individual die.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] It will always overestimate the true best-case gross DPW, since it includes the area of partially patterned dies which do not fully lie on the wafer surface (see figure).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] These partially patterned dies don't represent complete ICs, so they usually cannot be sold as functional parts.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Refinements of this simple formula typically add an edge correction, to account for partial dies on the edge, which in general will be more significant when the area of the die is large compared to the total area of the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] In the other limiting case (infinitesimally small dies or infinitely large wafers), the edge correction is negligible.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] (area ratio scaled by a polynomial factor).
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] While silicon is the prevalent material for wafers used in the electronics industry, other compound III-V or II-VI materials have also been employed.
[src:semiconductor-fabrication/wafer-electronics] Gallium arsenide (GaAs), a III-V semiconductor produced via the Czochralski method, gallium nitride (GaN) and silicon carbide (SiC) are also common wafer materials, with GaN and sapphire being extensively used in LED manufacturing.
